<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-475-461  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 475 461.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  Sept 1990 v30 n9 p43(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Interface design for high bandwidth diagnosis: the case of POSIT.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Orey, Michael A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The design of POSIT (Process Oriented Subtraction Interface forTutoring) is based on the principle that begins with an interfaceand builds the system around that interface.andP;  Bandwidth is thediscrepancy between internal mental states and observablebehaviors.andP;  High bandwidth is used to have a system that maps onto a one-to-one correspondence between internal mental states andobservable behaviors of the student.andP;  The interface in POSITapproaches high bandwidth in the domain of whole numbersubtraction.andP;  The child uses a computer mouse to point at any areaand clicks the mouse button to choose that area.andP;  Then the childtypes a number.andP;  This is the subtraction interface.andP;  The childalso can click on four on-screen buttons: restart, help, done, andquit.andP;  POSIT's regrouping areas and the difference areas permit itto gain access to more mental states than other diagnosticsystems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EducationStudentSubtractorsBandwidthUser Interface.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The design of the interface. (chart)The use of the regrouping areas c9 and c10 for four-digitproblems. (chart)The use of the regrouping areas c9 and c10 for three-digitproblems. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>